-- ============================================================
-- SECTION 4: HOW THESE TABLES RELATE TO EACH OTHER
-- ============================================================
--
-- The governance schema tables are mostly related conceptually.
-- They are often not connected through strict foreign key constraints.
--
-- This is normal because governance tables are often:
--   - control tables
--   - audit tables
--   - registries
--   - logs
--
-- RELATIONSHIP VIEW
-- ------------------------------------------------------------
--
-- dataset_metadata answers:
--   "What is this dataset?"
--
-- asset_tag_registry answers:
--   "How is this dataset classified?"
--
-- dataset_lineage answers:
--   "Where did this dataset come from?"
--
-- schema_registry answers:
--   "Is the schema of this dataset controlled?"
--
-- pipeline_run_audit answers:
--   "Was the pipeline that refreshes this dataset executed properly?"
--
-- governance_certification_scorecard answers:
--   "Is this dataset governance-ready for release?"
--
-- ============================================================



-- ============================================================
-- SECTION 5: CONCEPTUAL RELATIONSHIP MAP
-- ============================================================
--
-- The central object in governance is usually the dataset name,
-- for example:
--   ecomsphere.gold.fact_sales_order_item
--   ecomsphere.silver.silver_dim_customer_profile
--
-- That dataset can appear in multiple governance tables.
--
-- CONCEPTUAL LINKS
-- ------------------------------------------------------------
--
-- dataset_metadata.full_name
-- is conceptually related to:
--   - asset_tag_registry.full_name
--   - dataset_lineage.upstream_object
--   - dataset_lineage.downstream_object
--   - schema_registry.dataset_name
--   - governance_certification_scorecard.dataset_name
--
-- pipeline_run_audit is slightly different because it tracks
-- pipeline task execution rather than dataset master records directly.
-- Still, it is operationally related because those tasks refresh
-- the datasets governed elsewhere.
--
-- ============================================================



-- ============================================================
-- SECTION 6: HOW THE GOVERNANCE SCHEMA GETS POPULATED END TO END
-- ============================================================
--
-- 6.1 DURING ENVIRONMENT / OBJECT SETUP
-- ------------------------------------------------------------
-- Usually populated:
--   - dataset_metadata
--   - initial dataset_lineage
--   - initial asset_tag_registry
--
-- Usually by:
--   - setup SQL scripts
--   - deployment notebooks
--   - governance registration scripts
--
--
-- 6.2 DURING INGESTION / TRANSFORMATION PIPELINE RUNS
-- ------------------------------------------------------------
-- Usually populated:
--   - pipeline_run_audit
--
-- Usually by:
--   - Airflow
--   - Databricks job/notebook logging
--
-- Most realistic for this project:
--   - Airflow controls the run
--   - Databricks executes the processing
--   - both contribute execution audit information
--
--
-- 6.3 DURING SCHEMA EVOLUTION MONITORING
-- ------------------------------------------------------------
-- Usually populated:
--   - schema_registry
--
-- Usually by:
--   - Auto Loader-aware schema comparison notebook/job
--   - governance approval process
--
--
-- 6.4 DURING TAGGING / METADATA UPDATE
-- ------------------------------------------------------------
-- Usually populated:
--   - asset_tag_registry
--   - sometimes dataset_metadata updates
--
-- Usually by:
--   - manual governance scripts
--   - metadata/tag sync notebooks
--   - classification workflows
--
--
-- 6.5 DURING GOVERNANCE REVIEW / RELEASE READINESS
-- ------------------------------------------------------------
-- Usually populated:
--   - governance_certification_scorecard
--
-- Usually by:
--   - governance reviewer
--   - release checklist notebook
--   - manual approval workflow
--
-- ============================================================



-- ============================================================
-- SECTION 7: END-TO-END GOVERNANCE FLOW IN SIMPLE LANGUAGE
-- ============================================================
--
-- Step 1:
-- A dataset is created in Bronze, Silver, or Gold.
--
-- Step 2:
-- The dataset is registered in dataset_metadata.
--
-- Step 3:
-- Classification labels may be recorded in asset_tag_registry.
--
-- Step 4:
-- Upstream/downstream relationships are recorded in dataset_lineage.
--
-- Step 5:
-- If the dataset is file-based and schema evolves, schema changes
-- are tracked in schema_registry.
--
-- Step 6:
-- Whenever pipeline execution happens, task-level execution events
-- are recorded in pipeline_run_audit.
--
-- Step 7:
-- Before governed release or signoff, the dataset is reviewed in
-- governance_certification_scorecard.
--
-- ============================================================



